description: These shrub-like trees were an important component of the shrubby and woodland ecosystems. The branches were thickly growing, and the saw-toothed leaves were compound and freshly green. This one was found under a large Coast Live Oak Woodland.

The plant was a shrub which was shrouded in gray-greenish, needle-like soft leaves, scented foliage, and semiwoody stems. Droplets of water hung from the foliage, creating a beautiful scenery in the Coastal Sage Scrub. Weeds and other shrubs often grew alongside these shrubs.
The shrub was deciduous, with green leaves, fleshy stems, and large, yellow flowers with brown, seedy centers. These were the dominant shrubs of the lower Coastal Sage Scrub.

The large shrub had long, thick, gray branches. It also had rounded, green, evergreen, saw-toothed leaves. These were rarely seen in the Chaparral, suggesting that their population there must've been minor in numbers.

The fungus grew along the side of an old snag, which resulted with interesting structures that sort of look like serrated "teeth". These were light tawny brown and dark brown/gray in coloration. The snags of the Coast Live Oak Woodlands were where these fungi were frequently spotted. This cluster was especially beautiful!
The succulent was very large, with large, thick, blue-green, needle-like leaves. They all grew outwards from a center core. These were abundant in the boulder-clad Chaparral landscape.
The shrub had large, thick, gray branches. It also had rounded, green, evergreen, saw-toothed leaves. These grew in the Coast Live Oak Woodland, among the leaf litter and weeds.

The shrub was large, and had thick, taco-like, green leaves. The flowers were in bloom, showing off the crimson/rose pink coloration. The branches were slim and light gray/pinkish red. This was the only individual I saw in this Chaparral.

The sage was prospering with new growth, the foliage was bright green, scented, and rough to the touch. The stems were brittle in the core, however fresh and flexible towards the shrub's crown. This species was one of the keystone plants of this Chaparral.

The plant was a buckwheat, because of the remains of reddish-brown flower heads. The tender, fresh, greening leaves were small and needlelike, along narrow, yet numerous stems. These grew into sometimes pure stands in the Chaparral.

The plant was a shrub which was shrouded in gray-greenish, needle-like soft leaves, scented foliage, and semiwoody stems. Droplets of water hung from the foliage, creating a beautiful scenery in the Coastal Sage Scrub. These artemisias do capture water pretty well with their foliage.

The tree's branches were thickly growing, and the saw-toothed leaves were compound and freshly green. These were growing frequently in the Chaparral, often merging the shrub lands and woodlands together.
The shrub was large, and its growth was dense. The branches were silvery gray, thin, and covered with small, bright green leaves. This shrub was distinctly different from the others in the Chaparral.

The plant was a shrub which was shrouded in gray-greenish, needle-like soft leaves, scented foliage, and semiwoody stems. Droplets of water hung from the greening foliage, creating a beautiful scenery in the Coastal Sage Scrub.

The parasitic plant was pesky, but under control in its natural environment. It was very stringy, and light orange in color. These were abundant in the Chaparral, I noticed that these grew in close association with buckwheats.

description:
Cute, discrete little cushions of a rather hoary moss growing on rock.  I love the sporophytes curling up and lying down on top.

The leaves are kind of ovate/lanceolate and have those long white awns which create the hoary look.

If you look at the the cells in the mid lower leaf they have wavy walls, one signature of the genus Grimmia. 

The cap on the sporophyte is very small and "mitrate" - it has little lobes. This was one character that lead me to G. pulvinata.

description: The snail near my finger.

This moss has tongue-shaped leaves which are relatively flat and have long white awns.

It is growing on the trunk of a coast live oak with a moss in the genus Orthotrichum .

In the cross-section of the leaf you can see the crescent shaped group of cells (stereid band) which have thick-walls at the bottom of the midrib - in the photo they appear a bit brownish. This crescent shape signals the genus Syntrichia. The relatively flat leaf and the presence of hydroid cells in the midrib indicate S. princeps.

description:
Super cool lichen growing on relatively flat soil in the shade of coast live oaks.

Both the squamules and podetia are quite stiff and hard, unlike mosses and liverworts and hornworts which are much softer and fleshier.  Also, unlike the mosses, liverworts and hornworts which look significantly different when wet or dry (generally more shriveled when dry), this lichen looks essentially the same when wet or dry - just a slight color change.

description:
Super cute moss with tongue shaped leaves with long white awns. You can see in the photo how the awns capture water droplets. Plenty of tall straight sporophytes not quite mature yet. Growing in tufts on rock without much shade.

The leaf cross section shows the  elliptic shaped "stereid band" (the thick-walled cells which look yellowish in the photo) characteristic of the Tortula genus.

The photo of just the tip of the leaf is meant to show the relatively thick walled cells at the leaf margin - this would indicate T. muralis, along with the fact that the leaf margins are recurved nearly to the apex of the leaf as seen in the full leaf photo.
